name: Nick Szabo
tweet: @zdumienski My paper focused on England, Henry III (13c) to James I (early 17c). I also read some earlier Anglo-Saxon cases, broadly similar early Normans'. Earlier rights were even closer to allodial; I cover a quo warranto case disputing allodial title ("my sword is my warrant!")

name: Nick Szabo
tweet: @zdumienski Anthropologists tended to be pretty free-wheeling, sentimental, and paternalistic with their translations into English of such words.  (For example "gift".  Neolithic-tech peoples weren't children swapping "gifts" under a Christmas tree).

name: Nick Szabo
tweet: @zdumienski In the earliest court documents almost every legal right was a property right. Trend was to be less so as centuries rolled on. Almost every economic & political right from land to servitude to jurisdictional powers to having priests pray for you was a subject of property law.

name: Nick Szabo
tweet:
@zdumienski I've read many medieval English court cases. There is no allusion in them to "community" or any such romantic ideology. It's about property rights & evidence & legal issues with same.

Terms like "pubic interest" came to be applied to a lord's jurisdictional powers, much later.

name: Nick Szabo
tweet: @zdumienski Beer, wine, and similar had a crucial practical function, a source of clean water in otherwise poorly hygienic villages or towns. The psychoactivity is optional, as much of East Asia used tea for the same function.

name: Nick Szabo
tweet:
